{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511537"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:43:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11752"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.55,0.3,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35622"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of pain in his right index finger. He reports that, while playing weekend cricket, a fast-moving ball struck the tip of the finger and forced it to bend further than usual. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as an accountant and plays recreational cricket weekly. He does not smoke or use alcohol to excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO\u2082 99 % on room air, and temperature 36.7 \u00b0C. The distal interphalangeal joint of the right index finger is swollen and tender (Image 1-2). There is no active extension at that joint, although passive extension is preserved. Capillary refill is less than two seconds and sensation is intact throughout the digit. Plain radiography shows no fracture or joint subluxation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flexor digitorum profundus tendon","Median nerve","Terminal slip of extensor digitorum tendon","Extensor indicis tendon","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETerminal slip of extensor digitorum tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for active extension of the distal interphalangeal joint. A direct axial load that forcibly flexes the fingertip can rupture this tendon, producing the classic mallet deformity with loss of active extension but preserved passive motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor digitorum profundus tendon\u003C/strong\u003E flexes, rather than extends, the distal interphalangeal joint; its rupture (the \u2018jersey finger\u2019) causes inability to flex the fingertip, opposite to the presentation described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E injury would cause broader motor deficits (thenar weakness, loss of thumb opposition) and sensory loss in the radial three-and-a-half digits, none of which is present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor indicis tendon\u003C/strong\u003E lies proximal to the distal interphalangeal joint and mainly extends the metacarpophalangeal joint of the index finger. Its isolated rupture would not selectively abolish distal interphalangeal extension while sparing other joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E palsy impairs intrinsic hand muscles and sensation in the ulnar one-and-a-half digits; isolated distal interphalangeal joint extension loss of the index finger would not be explained by this nerve injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mallet finger results from rupture of the terminal slip of the extensor mechanism, preventing active extension at the distal interphalangeal joint.","Hyperflexion force to the fingertip during ball sports is the typical mechanism of injury.","Differentiating tendon injury from nerve injury relies on focal loss of movement without widespread motor or sensory deficit."],"references":["Orthobullets. Mallet Finger. Orthobullets. Updated October 21, 2024. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6014/mallet-finger","American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons. Mallet Finger (Baseball Finger) [Internet]. Rosemont, IL: OrthoInfo; 2023 May [cited 2025 May 9]. Available at: https://orthoinfo.aaos.org/en/diseases--conditions/mallet-finger-baseball-finger/","Alla SR, Deal ND, Dempsey IJ. Current concepts: mallet finger. Hand (N Y). 2014 Jun;9(2):138-44. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4022957/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20079"},{"type":"media","id":"20080"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20079"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d36547f0-5af9-4437-a180-b1a0a5073bde.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d36547f0-5af9-4437-a180-b1a0a5073bde.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":396,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/m